<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Artemisia</i> <i>californica</i> and <i>Salvia</i> <i>mellifera</i> are co-dominant in the shrub canopy with <i>Adenostoma</i> <i>fasciculatum</i>, <i>Diplacus</i> <i>aurantiacus</i>, <i>Encelia</i> <i>californica</i>, <i>Eriogonum</i> <i>fasciculatum</i>, <i>Hesperoyucca</i> <i>whipplei</i>, <i>Lotus</i> <i>scoparius</i>, <i>Malosma</i> <i>laurina</i>, <i>Rhus</i> <i>integrifolia</i>, <i>Rhus</i> <i>ovata</i> and <i>Salvia</i> <i>apiana</i>. Emergent taller shrubs may be present at low cover. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs are < 2 m and sometimes two tiered; canopy is intermittent to continuous. Herbaceous layer is variable. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li>Both <i>Artemisia californica</i> and <i>Salvia mellifera</i> 30%-60% relative cover in the shrub canopy (Evens and San 2005, Gordon and White 1994, Klein and Evens 2005).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Steep, east- to southwest-facing slopes. Soils are usually colluvial derived.  </div>
</div>

        
