<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Artemisia californica </i>is a much-branched shrub up to 2 m tall with shallow roots. Leaves have a strong aroma and are gray green, soft, and entire to divided into narrow, linear segments. Leaves are drought deciduous and seasonally dimorphic. Leaves, shrub litter, and the soil below the shrubs contain chemicals that inhibit germination or growth of some plants. Herbivores and seed eaters may contribute to conspicuous bare zones seen at the edge of shrub crowns. Seeds of these fall-blooming plants are dispersed in the winter and spring. They germinate best under lighted conditions and when fresh. Seeds germinate in canopy openings, and seedlings suffer high mortality from herbivory (Montalvo 2002a). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Salvia mellifera </i>is an open, shallow-rooted shrub that grows to 2 m in height. Twigs and leaves are glandular and highly aromatic. Plants produce numerous volatile compounds that may be important in herbivore or pathogen defense. They are drought tolerant by leaf curling rather than through leaf drop (Gill and Hanlon 1998), but they are still considered to have a suite of drought-deciduous characteristics by Rundel (2007). Winter- and spring-blooming flowers are a rich source of nectar for native and introduced bees. Gravity and ants disperse seeds, which collect in the soil as a seed bank. Seeds often have low germination rates unless exposed to light or components of fire, but heat from fire may reduce germination rates (Keeley and Fotheringham 1998). Seedlings establish in clearings among older shrubs when soils are moist. Plants take two or more growing seasons to reach maturity. Plants sometimes sprout from the base. Recruitment is primarily by seed (Montalvo and McMillan 2002b). <br/>
<br/>
The alliance is represented throughout most of its range by a single association in which the two nominate species comprise the majority of the shrub cover. Despite regional variation in associated species, only one additional association is known at this time. The alliance is generally found on moderate-to-steep, low-elevation slopes that have been burned within the last four decades (Gordon and White 1994). See general discussions in Mooney (1977) and Rundel (2007). </div>
</div>

    
	
	
