<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Fire Characteristics</h4>
	<div class="text">After lower-intensity fires, both <i>Artemisia californica </i>and <i>Salvia mellifera </i>sprout moderately well, and stands are likely to survive and regenerate through root crown sprouting (Gordon and White 1994, McMurray 1990e). After higher-severity fire, both species regenerate mostly from soil-stored seed. However, <i>S. mellifera </i>has more adaptive seeding ability and can reoccupy sites rapidly; <i>A. californica </i>seedling emergence is much lower after high-intensity fire than is <i>S. mellifera </i>(Gordon and White 1994, Montalvo 2002a, McMurray 1990e). 

In addition, post-burn reestablishment varies geographically. Both species sprout more often in lowerelevation maritime sites where coastal sage scrub are more common than in higher-elevation inland sites where chaparral is more common (Westman 1991, Malanson and O’Leary 1982, Keeley and Keeley 1984).</div>
	<table class="zebraStripe">
		
		<tr>
			<td class="key">Fire return interval</td>
			<td>Medium (20-70+ years)
				
			</td>
		</tr>
		
