    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Aj-l). Stands occur in the southern Santa Lucia Mountains.</li>
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Aa-h, Aj). Stand descriptions come from Coyote Ridge (Evens and San 2004) and the San Benito Mountain area (Evens et al. 2006) of the Diablo Range. Stands in the southern subsections need sampling.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Ba-j). Stand descriptions come from the Santa Monica Mountains (Keeler- Wolf and Evens 2006), western San Diego Co. (Evens and San 2005), and generally for the section (DeSimone and Burk 1992).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Ba, Bc-d, Bf, Bj-k, Bn). Stands occur in western Riverside Co. (Klein and Evens 2005) and generally across the section (DeSimone and Burk 1992, Gordon and White 1994, Kirkpatrick and Hutchinson 1977).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Stands of <i>Artemisia californica </i>and <i>Salvia mellifera </i>are decreasing in wildlands because of increased fire frequency, a presence of non-native grasses including <i>Bromus rubens</i>, and air pollution. Successful restoration efforts need to create conditions where shrubs can establish, mature, and develop seed banks (Montalvo 2002a, Montalvo and McMillan 2002b). </div>
</div>

    

    

